Weight lifting used to be a majority of my lifestyle. Around 5 years ago, I eased up. Then the pandemic hit, I was done. I really dialed in on my career and lost sight of the thing that brought me the most joy. The last few months, I’ve been dialing in to make weight lifting a part of my routine. I’ve dialed in on just being active again. One of the biggest obstacles of my life has never been prioritizing my work, but prioritizing myself the last few years 🧠 I hated feeling like I wasn’t an athlete anymore, I was just around them. The last photo- in 2017/18, I was the strongest I’ve been. I’ll hit new goals this time around, but I’m fucking back ❤️‍🔥 I had to step away a learn some new shit. Shouout to @tremontathletic for letting me lift some weights and put them back down yesterday at the facility and @d_criswelll for letting me rock with him.

With the 49th pick in the 2023 NBA Draft, the @cavs select @emoni21 The first player I started covering consistently? Emoni Bates. First @slam feature? Emoni Bates. Countless miles put on my car, time away from the fam, dialed into my craft. It all made me who I am today. I think player relations are important and I think this guy is a huge reason why I’m NOT just in photo + video anymore. I can’t put into words how I feel about having this dude in Cleveland now, but until then; I’m proud of you G. YOU put in the work 🦍 Forever and always appreciative for trusting me to do my thing 🤞🏽❤️‍🔥 Let’s run it back

November 8th will be my last day working at ESPN Cleveland. Starting November 9th, I will be taking on a new adventure. 

I’ve been dreaming about this exact moment for as long as I can remember. 

After Thanksgiving I will be working on-site at Seaport studios working with ESPN Radio , ESPN Podcasts, and working with on-air talent to help build their communities across social. 

For so long I built my own brand around photo + video, where in reality - I’ve always been working behind the scenes on anything and everything to take me to the next level. This is that next level. 

I need some more recommendations on living spaces- but New York, I can’t wait to call you home🗽

As someone who wears a lot of hats, I pay attention to a lot of the details. From when I step into an arena, to when I leave. Game speed is such a fundamental building block in taking a player to the next level. Through my eyes, that’s how I also take my work and networking to the next level. I arrive hours before games, I stay long after games. From pregame practice reps, to game time. I’m dialed in on game speed situations to stay ready for whatever may happen throughout the game. You have to pay attention to the details 🧠

With what I do, I get what I put in. 

In my job, in my professional relationships, in my personal relationships. I’m sure you feel the same way. I wasn’t originally going to post about this - but I feel like it’s needed for the things that are often glorified. What I do is often glorified. I love what I do, but it’s often hard to describe what I do due to the amount of hats I’ve always had to wear. I’m not just a photographer, videographer, a social manager, someone who works with marketing, sales, player relations, etc. 

For that, I’m thankful. 

I feel lethal with whatever I put my mind to. However, it took a tremendous amount of sacrifice to get to where I am and I think it’s important to communicate that to everyone who wants to be one of the best at what they do. My path isn’t your path. However, I’m getting better about talking about what I had to give up to get to one of the places I want to be. 

As I grow… I’m embracing change, over communication, time management and utilization. I haven’t found a way to balance everything in my life quite yet, but I’m growing. That makes me feel lethal, because I know what I put in and where I want to be.

My laptop is NOT being opened inside my apartment. Okay, maybe it has once or twice… but I’m getting really good with turning it off or finding more mobile ways to work. Working at home was such a downfall to not only myself, but the people around me. So I’ve been implementing rules for myself at mi casa. 

- No editing inside my apartment 
- Only opening my laptop if I need to send something to my phone for later 
- Communicating with people around me if I need to go and work outside of 5a-5p 
- Making time for 10k steps a day 
- Hitting the gym every day 

Let me know your rules. If you’re in the city, where are your favorite places to work? ⬇️
